orbital launches were completed by flight-proven (reused) Falcon rockets.\n\n**Specific 2025 Launch Metrics:**\n*   **Falcon 9 Cadence:** 165 Falcon 9 rockets launched.\n*   **Booster Reuse:** 157 (or 159, as cited in a different paragraph) flight-proven booster launches.\n*   **Government/NASA Missions:** Launched 11 of 12 National Security Space Launch (NSSL) medium/heavy lift missions, and all 5 U.S. crew and cargo missions to the ISS.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Payload Capacity & Cost Metrics\n**Vehicle Capacities:**\n*   **Falcon 9:** Contributes steadily at an average capacity of **13 metric tons** per mission to various orbits since 2023.\n*   **Starship V3:** Expected payload capacity of **100 metric tons** to Earth\'s orbit in a reusable configuration.\n*   **Starship V4 (Future):** Designed to double capacity to **200 metric tons**.\n*   **Dragon Cargo Spacecraft:** Launch payload mass of up to **6,000 kg**; return payload mass of up to **3,000 kg**.\n\n**Cost per Kilogram to Orbit:**\n*   **Historical Industry Average:** $18,500 per kg.\n*   **Falcon 9 (2010 debut):** Reduced cost to ~**$2,700 per kg** (an ~85% reduction).\n*   **Falcon Heavy (2018 debut):** Further reduced cost to ~**$1,400 per kg** (a ~92% reduction).\n*   **Starship (Future Goal):** Expected to reduce the cost to reach orbit by **99% or more** relative to the historical $18,500/kg average.\n\n**Future Orbital AI Compute Projections:**\n*   **Target Scale:** Transporting approximately **1 million metric tons to orbit annually** to support 100 gigawatts per year of orbital AI compute.\n*   **Compute Density:** Satellites designed to carry over **100 kilowatts of compute power per metric ton**.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Mission Success & Recovery Rates\n*   **Overall Mission Success Rate:** **>99%** across Falcon rockets.\n*   **Booster Recovery Success Rate:** **>99%** on attempted booster recoveries in 2025.\n*   **Starlink Satellite Reliability:** Achieves **99.9% average uptime** (survivability under vi