    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial disclosures, here is the detailed breakdown of the Space segment\'s revenue composition, the specific services included (and excluded), segment reporting, and revenue recognition policies.\n\n### 1. What Services are Included in Space Segment Revenue?\nThe Space segment\'s revenue **only** reflects external customer launches and activities. It is primarily composed of two main service categories:\n*   **Launch Services:** Deployment of payloads to intended orbits for both **commercial and government customers** (utilizing Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy).\n*   **Launch & Development:** Development of spacecraft and provision of launch and mission services specifically for **government agency space programs** (utilizing Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Starship, and Dragon).\n\n**What is EXCLUDED from the Space Segment?**\n*   **Starlink & Starshield:** Both Starlink (broadband/mobile internet) and Starshield (secure government/national security satellite networks) are **not** part of the Space segment. They are classified under the **Connectivity segment**.\n*   **Internal Starlink Launches:** The Company does *not* recognize inter-segment revenue for launching its own Starlink satellites. Instead, these launch costs are capitalized as Property, Plant, and Equipment (satellites) within the Connectivity segment and depreciated over time. \n\n---\n\n### 2. Space Segment Revenue Composition Breakdown\nSpace segment revenue is derived entirely from fixed-price contracts. The breakdown between the two service categories as a percentage of total Space revenue is as follows:\n\n| Service Category | Year Ended Dec 31, 2025 | Year Ended Dec 31, 2024 | Year Ended Dec 31, 2023 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Launch Services** *(Point in Time)* | 63.0% | 68.2% | 55.2% |\n| **Launch & Development** *(Over Time)* | 37.0% | 31.8% | 44.8% |\n| **Total Space Segment** | **100.0%** | **100.0%** | **100.0%** |\n\n*Note: The company expects Launch & Development to represent a larger portion of Space revenue in the future as it continues to serve long-term government contracts.*\n\n---\n\n### 3. Revenue Recognition Details\nThe Company recognizes Space revenue either at a "point in time" or "over time" depending on the nature of the contract:\n\n*   **Launch Services (Recognized at a Point in Time):** \n    *   **Trigger:** Revenue and costs are deferred and recognized only upon the successful launch or deployment of the customer’s payload to its intended orbit.\n    *   **Rationale:** This is due to the interchangeability of flight hardware and minimal unique engineering costs.\n    *   **Contract Length:** Fixed-price contracts typically range from 1 to 5 years.\n*   **Launch & Development (Recognized Over Time):**\n    *   **Trigger:** Revenue is recognized progressively as work is performed.\n    *   **Method:** The **cost-to-cost input method** (costs incurred to date, such as materials and labor hours, relative to the total estimated cost at completion).\n    *   **Rationale:** The Company\'s performance creates an asset with no alternative use, and the Company holds an enforceable right to payment for performance to date.\n    *   **Contract Length:** Fixed-price contracts typically range from 1 to 14 years.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Segment Reporting Details\nThe financial results highlight the separation between the Space segment (external launches/development) and the Connectivity segment (Starlink/Starshield).\n\n**Space Segment Financials:**\n*   **2025 Revenue:** $4,086 million \n*   **2024 Revenue Growth:** Increased by $239 million compared to 2023.\n*   **2023 Revenue:** $3,557 million\n*   **Profitability (2025):** Generated a loss from operations of $(657) million, but a positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $653 million. This includes the impact of funding $3,004 million in R&D for the next-generation Starship program.\n*   **Strategic Note:** Space revenue growth is intentionally lower than total company growth because the company prioritizes allocating its massive launch capacity to internal businesses (Connectivity and AI) rather than external customers.\n\n**Connectivity Segment Financials (Home of Starlink & Starshield):**\n*   **2025 Revenue:** $11.4 billion (recognized partially over time using the cost-to-cost method for Starshield, and ratably/usage-based for Starlink).\n*   **2023 Revenue:** $3,869 million.\n*   **Profitability (2025):** Generated income from operations of $4,423 million and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $7,168 million.',
