    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided S-1 Preamble, Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements, and MD&A sections, the Company (SpaceX) operates **three reportable segments** within its "vertically integrated innovation engine": **Space**, **Connectivity**, and **AI**. \n\nHere are the definitions, inclusions, and MD&A/footnote discussions for each segment:\n\n### 1. Space Segment\n*   **Definition:** The Space segment "designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets to provide high cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale." The preamble specifically defines it to include "customer launch operations and offerings and services that utilize or support space-based infrastructure and capabilities, including launch services, satellite systems, and space-enabled technologies."\n*   **What is Included (MD&A & Footnote Details):**\n    *   **Revenue Breakdown:** Revenue is split into **Launch Services** (recognized at a point in time) and **Launch & Development** (recognized over time, primarily tied to long-term government contracts). *Note: Space segment revenue only reflects customer launches and activities; internal launches (e.g., launching Starlink satellites) are not recorded as Space revenue.*\n    *   **Vehicles & Hardware:** Includes the Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, and Dragon spacecraft. It also includes the next-generation **Starship** program, which is currently in the development stage.\n    *   **Cost of Revenue:** Includes non-reusable second stages, launch operations and overhead, depreciation of reusable hardware (boosters, fairings, Merlin engines), and testing/engineering costs.\n    *   **Research & Development (R&D):** R&D is heavily concentrated on the development, build, and testing of **Starship** and Raptor engines, as well as launch site infrastructure. The MD&A notes that Starship costs are currently expensed as R&D but will be capitalized and depreciated into Cost of Revenue once the vehicle is commercialized.\n    *   **Financial Trends:** Space revenue growth is expected to lag behind total company growth because internal demand (launching Starlink satellites and AI infrastructure) absorbs most of the company\'s launch capacity. Segment Adjusted EBITDA has recently faced downward pressure due to accelerated, heavily expensed investments in Starship and new launch facilities.\n\n### 2. Connectivity Segment\n*   **Definition:** The Connectivity segment "operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit, delivering connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers."\n*   **What is Included (MD&A & Footnote Details):**\n    *   **Revenue Streams:** Generated from (i) broadband and mobile connectivity services (including "Starlink Mobile" for satellite-to-mobile texting and voice) and (ii) the sale of hardware/Starlink Kits (inclusive of the user terminal). Services are billed via fixed-price subscriptions or variable-priced data consumption.\n    *   **Customer Base:** Includes "Starlink Consumer Broadband," enterprise, and government customers across 164 countries and territories.\n    *   **Cost of Revenue:** Driven primarily by the volume spend on manufacturing Starlink Kits and the **depreciation of capitalized satellite costs** as the constellation grows and satellites are placed into orbit.\n    *   **Financial Trends:** This segment is a massive growth and profitability engine. The MD&A highlights strong year-over-year revenue and Adjusted EBITDA growth driven by subscriber expansion, enterprise adoption, and network efficiency. It became Segment Adjusted EBITDA positive on a sustained basis beginning in 2023.\n\n### 3. AI Segment\n*   **Definition:** The AI segment "operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning a frontier LLM Grok, AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, X — a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform — and AI computational infrastructure."\n*   **What is Included (MD&A & Footnote Details):**\n    *   **Offerings & Revenue:** Includes the Grok LLM (with "Grok Business" and "Grok Enterprise" sold on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing models), X platform subscriptions, advertising sales, and data licensing arrangements.\n    *   **Cost of Revenue & R&D:** Dominated by massive computational infrastructure costs. The MD&A explicitly cites the **depreciation of GPU hardware**, cloud computing costs, and data center infrastructure expansions as the primary drivers of the segment\'s operating losses and R&D expenses.\n    *   **Financial Trends:** Described as a "newly acquired" segment where the company plans to "prioritize growth and investment." It currently operates at a significant loss from operations and negative Adjusted EBITDA due to heavy capital expenditures (e.g., $7.7 billion in CapEx for Q1 2026 alone) tied to AI data center build-outs.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Segment Interdependence (Capital Allocation Strategy)\nThe Preamble\'s "Capital Allocation and Funding Strategy" section outlines how these segments interact as a self-reinforcing cycle:\n1.  **Space** serves as the "backbone" for the Connectivity segment by providing the launch vehicles required to build the Starlink constellation.\n2.  Capital generated from Space (alongside external equity) funded the **Connectivity** segment, which now generates predictable, recurring cash flow.\n3.  The company is now leveraging its scale to reinvest heavily into the nascent **AI** segment and next-generation Space infrastructure (Starship) to capture new market opportunities.',
